Samsonvale cemetery and surrounds, Samsonvale cemetery is accessed off Mt Samson Rd and is situated at the end of Golds Scrub Lane. This site also includes Kobble Creek Rest Area on Mt Samson Rd and the end of Postmans Track. This area is where Kobble Creek feeds Lake Samsonvale at its western end. Habitat includes rank grassland, and various forest types. Good area for quail and raptors and has turned up some western vagrants.

Winton Wetlands, A former irrigation reservoir at Chesney Vale commissioned in 1970. The reservoir (known as Lake Mokoan) flooded the original wetlands of Winton Swamp and Green Swamp, and a series of smaller swamps in the complex. The lake had unacceptable losses of water through evaporation and problems with blue-green algae so after a lengthy process was decommissioned on October 14th 2010. The site was renamed Winton Wetlands (after the original swamp) and is currently in the process of being rehabilitated to a series of shallow red gum wetlands and grassy box woodland around the edges. The site supports a wide variety of wetland and bush species. Also includes 10 child sites which are bird monitoring points for the wetlands.

Cairns Esplanade, The foreshore area of Cairns called the Esplanade overlooks the mainly muddy tidal flats with some grassy areas. The area also includes the mangrove swamps on the Northern end of the Esplanade. Easily the best place to observe shorebirds (waders) in comfort from a park bench within the city. Best time for migratory shorebirds is late August-March but some species resident all year.

Kedron Brook Wetlands, A series of saltwater to brakish lagoons between Cannery Creek, Shultz canal and Kedron Brook Floodway. The lagoons undergo a series of filling and drying events throughout the year and are surrounded by saltmarsh, mangrove, casuarina and grassland habitat. Access off Toombul Rd, easy to walk as access track circles area and grasslands are crisscrossed with mown tracks.

FRAZER 1' Cell, Much of the area is riparian zone beside the meandering Gold Creek. The altitude goes from about 20m to 120m above sea-level. There are open eucalypt forests, lowland rainforests, horse paddocks, large lawn areas, large dams, woodlands. There are ridges and valleys. The land has been extensively cultivated in some areas.

Bowra Station, Bowra contains a range of habitats including Mulga. It is owned by Australian Wildlife Conservancy. AWC welcome people interested in nature particularly birds and native plants. Limited accommodation camping sites are available. Inquiries and bookings should be made on 07 4655 1238 or by contacting AWC by phone or email. The Sanctuary is closed from November to February inclusive. During summer inquiries for the next year can be made on 07 3398 5118 The property list is around 200 species.
